dispelling the myths surrounding her.Drawing on a wealth of archival evidence, Stollberg-Rilinger examines all facets of eighteenth-century society, from piety and patronage to sexuality and childcare, ceremonial life at court, diplomacy, and the everyday indignities of warfare. She challenges the idealized image of Maria Theresa as an enlightened reformer and mother of her lands who embodied both feminine beauty and virile bellicosity, showing how she despised the ideas of the Enlightenment, treated her children with relentless austerity, and mercilessly persecuted Protestants and Jews. Work, consistent physical and mental discipline, and fear of God were the principles Maria Theresa lived by, and she demanded the same from her family, her court, and her subjects.A panoramic work of scholarship that brings Europe's age of empire spectacularly to life, Maria Theresa paints an unforgettable portrait of the uncompromising yet singularly charismatic woman who left her enduring mark on the era in which she lived and reigned.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAustria-History-Maria Theresa, 1740-1780. 0aAustria-Kings and rulers-Biography. 0aMaria Theresa,-Empress of Austria,-1717-1780. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Austria & Hungary.2bisacsh  aAdviser.  aAnschluss.  aApathy.  aArchduke.  aAristocracy.  aAulic Council.  aCabinet noir.  aCensorship.  aCivilian.  aClementia.  aConsummation.  aCourt painter.  aCourtesy.  aCourtier.  aCriticism.  aDeportation.  aDespotism.  aDissolution of the Monasteries.  aDistrust.  aEdict of toleration.  aEdict.  aEducation.  aEgocentrism.  aElector of Mainz.  aElectorate of Saxony.  aExcommunication.  aFlattery.  aFoot the bill.  aFormality.  aGiacomo Casanova.  aGod.  aGodparent.  aGrandee.  aGreat power.  aHeresy.  aHofburg